they realize, 'Hey. We've done it before.
We know what it takes within this room to

00:32:50.340 --> 00:32:57.140
win.' But you also have to guard against complacency
which so far, you look at the way Tim Lincecum

00:32:57.140 --> 00:33:00.840
has pitched and he hasn't pitched complacent
at all. You look at Aubrey Huff – maybe

00:33:00.840 --> 00:33:04.720
putting on a few pounds and you wonder, 'Has
he allowed himself to get a little complacent?'

00:33:04.720 --> 00:33:09.130
And he obviously is off to a bad start. So
there's some guys because their personality

00:33:09.130 --> 00:33:14.200
might affect in different ways and that's
probably Bochy's biggest challenge is to guard

00:33:14.200 --> 00:33:18.810
against that complacency and stop them from
thinking, 'Well, it worked out for us last

00:33:18.810 --> 00:33:22.230
year. So we'll just skip the work and it'll
work out for us again.' Because obviously

00:33:22.230 --> 00:33:29.091
that isn't the way it works.
In terms of trading for José Reyes, it's

00:33:29.091 --> 00:33:33.500
not realistic because if you trade for someone
at this point in the year, you have to massively

00:33:33.500 --> 00:33:37.790
overpay for them. I think the Mets know that
a number of teams are gonna want a José Reyes.

00:33:37.790 --> 00:33:41.150
They're probably going to give up a number
of minor league players. Right now, if the

00:33:41.150 --> 00:33:44.320
Giants want to get a José Reyes, it's gonna
cost them Zach Wheeler and Brandon Belt which

00:33:44.320 --> 00:33:47.870
is their top pitcher and hitting prospect.
And that's – no way that's gonna happen.

00:33:47.870 --> 00:33:53.480
And if you look at Brian Sabean's resume as
a General Manager, he'll give up prospects.

00:33:53.480 --> 00:33:57.800
He will give up players who were regarded
in this minor league system but he'll give

00:33:57.800 --> 00:34:02.170
them up for players that he can plug in for
a few years. And when they trade for AJ Pierzynski,

00:34:02.170 --> 00:34:06.250
they thought AJ'd be one of those guys. He
wasn't eligible for free agency for several

00:34:06.250 --> 00:34:11.510
years. He was arbitration eligible. Well obviously,
he was a gigantic failure in his one year

00:34:11.510 --> 00:34:15.730
as a Giant and they got rid of him.
But José Reyes would be a Giant basically

00:34:15.730 --> 00:34:18.730
until the end of the year and he knows he
would make a hundred million dollars on the

00:34:18.730 --> 00:34:23.050
open market. There's no way you're gonna sign
him to a contract before he would hit free

00:34:23.050 --> 00:34:28.100
agency. And so for the Giants to get him,
if they do, it's gonna be right at the trade

00:34:28.100 --> 00:34:32.640
deadline which is July 31st, and it's going
to have to mean that they don't have a whole

00:34:32.640 --> 00:34:36.520
lot of competition for him because I don't
see them giving up a lot of their premium

00:34:36.520 --> 00:34:40.790
prospects. And Bill Neukom is the new owner.
And he's made building from within the farm

00:34:40.790 --> 00:34:44.690
system such a huge priority. So I don't see
that happening. They're gonna have to probably

00:34:44.690 --> 00:34:48.120
muddle through and maybe get a lesser shortstop
if there's – there's no question that they

00:34:48.120 --> 00:34:51.639
have a problem at shortstop and that Tejada
is best suited at third base.

00:34:51.639 --> 00:34:53.440
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #5: Hi.
&gt;&gt;Andrew Baggarly: Hi.

00:34:53.440 --> 00:34:56.840
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #5: I was just kinda
curious – do you have a sense for, for how

00:34:56.840 --> 00:35:03.100
much the front office is using some of these
advance stats – like Sabermetrics, the UZR,

00:35:03.100 --> 00:35:05.170
Devor, to kind of analyze and manage their
players?

00:35:05.170 --> 00:35:10.430
&gt;&gt;Andrew Baggarly: Yeah. I think they are.
