00:35:10.430 --> 00:35:17.230
a lot less than other organizations. But they
do. It is part of the calculus. I think that

00:35:17.230 --> 00:35:21.370
Brian Sabean trusts his scouts more than anybody.
And when he's making a decision at the end

00:35:21.370 --> 00:35:25.640
of the day, he'll take it into account but
I don't think he allows himself to be swayed

00:35:25.640 --> 00:35:30.030
if he has a strong opinion already. There
are a couple of people in the front office

00:35:30.030 --> 00:35:34.830
who, who do a lot of analytics. In fact they
do a lot of their own analytics and they won't

00:35:34.830 --> 00:35:41.580
even talk about their methods. So Jeremy Shelley
is one. Yeshayah Goldfarb is another.

00:35:41.580 --> 00:35:47.840
So they, they do delve into that and it's
a part of, of player evaluation. And Bill

00:35:47.840 --> 00:35:54.150
Neukom being someone who was from, on the
ground floor of Microsoft and understands

00:35:54.150 --> 00:35:59.450
the value of information, is somebody who
is going to continue to champion that and

00:35:59.450 --> 00:36:05.610
make sure that is a part of player evaluation
and baseball operations. But knowing Brian

00:36:05.610 --> 00:36:10.760
Sabean the way I do, I think that he's open
minded to it. But if he has a strong opinion,

00:36:10.760 --> 00:36:15.750
he's going to go with the scouts most times
and his scouts obviously served him very well

00:36:15.750 --> 00:36:21.470
last year both in the players that they got
and the reports that they had on how best

00:36:21.470 --> 00:36:25.410
to attack some of the hitters that they faced
in the post-season.

00:36:25.410 --> 00:36:29.040
But I've tried to ask them and they're very
secretive about, about their methods. They

00:36:29.040 --> 00:36:33.790
don't want to say exactly what they really
place a high priority on. But they did tell

00:36:33.790 --> 00:36:39.610
me that there are some formulas that they've
created that are even non-proprietary. Things

00:36:39.610 --> 00:36:42.050
that are just in-house that they, that they
do use.

00:36:42.050 --> 00:36:47.320
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #6: Hi. I love your
blog. I wanted to ask you how as a reporter

00:36:47.320 --> 00:36:50.850
you deal with guys who have sort of fallen
out of favor with the club. Guys like Fred

00:36:50.850 --> 00:36:55.160
Lewis and Travis Ishikawa, and Kevin Franzen.
Could you just tell us a little bit about

00:36:55.160 --> 00:36:59.330
your experience with guys like that?
&gt;&gt;Andrew Baggarly: Yeah. I mean it's -- these

00:36:59.330 --> 00:37:04.290
guys are professionals. I would have a very
hard time covering college sports to be honest.

00:37:04.290 --> 00:37:08.900
And there's nothing wrong with covering college
sports on the beat. Obviously, I love to know

00:37:08.900 --> 00:37:15.860
about my alma mater and -- but it's very difficult
to cover college sports I think because you

00:37:15.860 --> 00:37:19.430
have to write critically about, about players
and when they're making millions of dollars,

00:37:19.430 --> 00:37:23.070
it's a little bit easier to write critically
about them because they realize it's part

00:37:23.070 --> 00:37:29.250
of the bargain. They get to live the lifestyle
and they get the benefits for their family

00:37:29.250 --> 00:37:33.470
and if it means that when they go 0 for 4
and strike out with the bases loaded and I

00:37:33.470 --> 00:37:39.610
ask them about it, it's not fun to be quizzed
on failing in front of 40,000 people but that's

00:37:39.610 --> 00:37:44.260
part of the bargain that you sign when you
are a major league player. So it's a little

00:37:44.260 --> 00:37:48.030
bit easier because you get cooperation from
the players. The ones that are professionals,

00:37:48.030 --> 00:37:53.561
the ones that understand my job – as long
as you're fair and you don’t take a lot

00:37:53.561 --> 00:37:59.190
of unnecessary cheap shots and you're accurate,
then, then you really have nothing to worry

00:37:59.190 --> 00:38:05.110
about. But there are, there are days when
we get yelled at and sometimes realize that

00:38:05.110 --> 00:38:09.310
has to happen because if it doesn't happen,
I'm probably not doing my job the right way.

00:38:09.310 --> 00:38:14.060
When it comes to players who have fallen out
of favor with the organization, you just try

00:38:14.060 --> 00:38:20.060
to put things in context. And if it's a player
who is on the outs and you kind of realize

00:38:20.060 --> 00:38:23.530
it, well, then you're writing who's going
to get playing time and who's not. And in

00:38:23.530 --> 00:38:28.570
the case of Fred Lewis or a Kevin Franzen,
obviously they weren't in the organization's

00:38:28.570 --> 00:38:33.800
plans and you just try to put that in context.
You give people the right expectations for

00:38:33.800 --> 00:38:38.310
who's gonna be out there on a given day. And
not only do fans want that, but people with

00:38:38.310 --> 00:38:42.810
fantasy teams too. [audience chuckles] They
want to know who to draft so that all goes

00:38:42.810 --> 00:38:47.350
into it. But whenever you're dealing with
a player who's struggling oftentimes it'll

00:38:47.350 --> 00:38:51.180
be someone who's a nice guy. Aaron Rowand
is a very, very nice guy. And he's had his

00:38:51.180 --> 00:38:56.890
struggles as a Giant and you have to write
about that. And this is part of the job and

00:38:56.890 --> 00:39:01.000
that's when you just hope that you're as professional
as you can be and the players as professional

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:03.450
as they can be too.
So…

