00:40:24.730 --> 00:40:25.730
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #7 : To go back to
the Brian Wilson question, what's that new

00:40:25.730 --> 00:40:30.040
pitch that he has? I know he doesn't have
a name for it but what would someone who knows

00:40:30.040 --> 00:40:37.360
baseball call it?
&gt;&gt;Andrew Baggarly: Well, he refuses to label

00:40:37.360 --> 00:40:43.390
his pitches. Even the pitch that he, he threw
to strike out Ryan Howard to win the NLCS.

00:40:43.390 --> 00:40:47.550
Was it a slider or was it a cutter? And he
referred to it as both. And I kind of – I

00:40:47.550 --> 00:40:51.170
don't think he wants anybody to know what
he's doing but the pitch that he's throwing

00:40:51.170 --> 00:40:56.290
that's really sort of diving in on the hands
of a lefty – that's sort of a two seam fastball.

00:40:56.290 --> 00:41:01.130
I think – and it's just got a lot of run
to it. And that's pretty much what it is.

00:41:01.130 --> 00:41:07.240
And you realize that Dave Righetti, the Giants
pitching coach, probably is doing a lot more

00:41:07.240 --> 00:41:10.330
behind the scenes than people realize. 'Cause
there are a lot of people who are throwing

00:41:10.330 --> 00:41:15.990
that pitch not only in the Major Leagues but
in the minor league organization too. And

00:41:15.990 --> 00:41:20.240
it's, it's one of the reasons the Giants give
up so few home runs. Not only because they

00:41:20.240 --> 00:41:24.350
have a big home run, a big home ball park
but because a lot of guys are keeping the

00:41:24.350 --> 00:41:27.730
ball down and that's a big pitch for a lot
