00:41:27.730 --> 00:41:32.020
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #8: Can you demonstrate
the difference between a cutter and a slider

00:41:32.020 --> 00:41:36.560
and a four seam fastball and a two seam fastball
and a slerve and all those other things?

00:41:36.560 --> 00:41:38.330
&gt;&gt;Andrew Baggarly: You gotta ball?
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #7: [laughs]

00:41:38.330 --> 00:41:42.340
&gt;&gt;Andrew Baggarly: It would be a little hard
without a ball. But basically a four seam

00:41:42.340 --> 00:41:47.400
fastball is a straight fastball. It's what
you throw with maximum velocity. It's one

00:41:47.400 --> 00:41:52.010
of the first pitch you learn to throw and
you try to learn to control it and work both

00:41:52.010 --> 00:41:56.620
sides of the plate. And you throw it across
the horseshoe so basically your finger's in

00:41:56.620 --> 00:42:02.670
contact with four seams which is why it's
called a 'four seamer'. A two seamer, you

00:42:02.670 --> 00:42:08.340
throw it with your fingers on the seams. Like
almost like a fork ball – you throw them

00:42:08.340 --> 00:42:11.720
outside the seams. They're right on the seams
for a two seamer. And because of the way the

00:42:11.720 --> 00:42:17.800
pressure, the finger pressure, it'll sink.
As it gets drag, it'll sink in the strike

00:42:17.800 --> 00:42:22.420
zone. So basically a two-seam fastball is
a sinker. And then a slider -- you have your

00:42:22.420 --> 00:42:27.119
two fingers together. You have them on one
seam and you're basically pushing it off and

00:42:27.119 --> 00:42:31.850
extending and that allows it to sort of sweep.
And then a curve ball you're throwing like

00:42:31.850 --> 00:42:34.890
that and that gets more twelve to six, they
say, break.

00:42:34.890 --> 00:42:39.140
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #7: What about a cutter?
&gt;&gt;Andrew Baggarly: And a cutter is basically

00:42:39.140 --> 00:42:43.600
a, a – I think it's just a four seam fast
ball but you have different pressure with

00:42:43.600 --> 00:42:48.369
the lower fingers or your thumb. I think,
basically, it just has to do with finger pressure

00:42:48.369 --> 00:42:53.280
more than anything else. And a cutter will
kind of have a little snap back. So it won't

00:42:53.280 --> 00:42:58.610
move completely straight like a four seamer
will. But there are times you want to throw

00:42:58.610 --> 00:43:02.230
it completely straight. I mean if Tim Lincecum
has two strikes on a guy and he really wants

00:43:02.230 --> 00:43:07.080
to blow him away and he wants to throw a four
seamer up here, that's a hard pitch to hit.

00:43:07.080 --> 00:43:10.710
And it's, it's a pitch designed to get a swing
and a miss because you are not going to get

00:43:10.710 --> 00:43:15.140
it called for a strike. [audience member coughs]
So that all goes into what do you throw and

00:43:15.140 --> 00:43:20.500
Buster Posey is a rookie catcher. And to make
all those decisions last year in big games

00:43:20.500 --> 00:43:26.400
and he knew the scouting reports inside and
out. The guy was honor roll, Presidential

00:43:26.400 --> 00:43:31.140
Honor Roll his whole time at Florida State.
He knew he was about to be drafted and get

00:43:31.140 --> 00:43:36.200
a 6 million dollar bonus and he kept taking
his, writing his papers and taking his finance

00:43:36.200 --> 00:43:42.680
degree anyway. And he was once asked by a
reporter from USA Today, he said, 'Other than

00:43:42.680 --> 00:43:46.150
school and baseball, what do you do?' And
he said, 'Well what else is there?' [audience

00:43:46.150 --> 00:43:50.570
laughter] So for him, he doesn't have the
school anymore so he's just, he's a student

00:43:50.570 --> 00:43:54.300
of the game and that's really, knowing those
scouting reports and knowing the pitchers'

00:43:54.300 --> 00:43:59.430
strengths and what to call was such a big
part of what they were able to do last year.

00:43:59.430 --> 00:44:04.970
